Context by mode:
- Two-team swap: Two isolated teams (Team A, Team B) each developed their own link-channel protocol over rounds 1..{{ boundary_round }}. After round {{ boundary_round }}, the two field observers were swapped between teams. Each team now has a new field observer who was not part of that team's protocol development. The swapped-in observer had been using their *own* team's protocol previously.
- Intern takeover: A single team developed a link-channel protocol over rounds 1..{{ boundary_round - 1 }}. The silent intern observed these rounds. From round {{ boundary_round }} onwards, the intern replaced the field observer and now communicates on the link.

What counts as "the protocol":
- Novel shorthand, abbreviations, letter/number codes for failure types or stabilization actions
- Structural conventions (e.g., "ACK"/"GO", numbered action lists, fixed slot orderings)
- Coined terms or jargon that consistently map to specific domain concepts
- Any regularity that the original pair clearly used to communicate efficiently

